<HEADLINE>
A Gruuling Week
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> EJH &lt;ejhaw...@ameritech.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-09T05:32:00 </POSTDATE>
August did not start particularly well. Our first Tuesday
session in Karazhan too too many tries to kill Moroes. This time,
my being slow to react to shackle breaks wasn't a factor: I was
on Dorandy that run, learning to hit #2 on the damage charts.
After taking three tries to down Maiden, it was time for bed.

As usual, my luck turned in the middle of the week. There was
a bit of confusion on Thursday which group I should go with:
the one I was with on Dorandy on Tuesday would start clearing
to Aran, the other group had made better time and already
cleared Aran and chess and would start clearing toward Prince.
I am eventually given to the Prince group, and head up the tower.

We get to the fight pretty quickly. After five tries or so,
Prince goes down. No hammers drop. I do, however, win the Tier 4
headpiece. We happily head down the tower to the Master's Terrace
for a crack at Nightbane. I still had Medivh's Journal from
killing Aran, so I read it while there; then we explained the fight
and got to it. Our learning curve is the same, Nightbane goes
down in five tries, only the second kill for Omani.

With lots of time left, we head back up the tower for a try
at the only Kara boss Omani has not yet killed, and may not
have seriously attempted, Netherspite. A recruit from a recently
busted guild that was much farther along in BC progression
explains the fight, which many of us have studied elsewhere.
There are two types of phases: beam phases and rage phases.
During beam phases, raiders must intercept energy beams to
deprive Netherspite of power and gain power of their own,
at a cost. During rage phases the MT and a couple of healers
keep him busy while the rest of the raid moves off and bandages.

A beam intercept rotation is set up: our druid MT takes the
red beam during the first beam phase, getting instant aggro
and 46k health. The green beam is taken by a pally in tanking
gear. The switch beams during the second beam phase, trading
thourghout the fight until the dragon is dead. The blue beam is
held for the first half of the first beam phase by the moonkin
doing all the explaining. For the rest of that phase a mage
takes it, getting heavy heals. For the even numbered beam
phases a warlock takes it all the way through, keeping himself
up with Drain Life.

It's a chaotic, fun fight. At one point I take the red beam,
getting 36k health, which dosen't last long. When I take the
green beam my mana pool goes down but my Renews tick for up
to 1600. Eventually, however, we get everything down, and
we get a guild first: Netherspite goes down! Kara is clear!
Much rejoicing.

One of the items that drops is a healing neck item no one
wants, so it gets pushed onto me. I am reluctant, having gotten
something already, and having now four neck items, one with
more +heal, another with more mana regen. This one, however, has
stamina, which I take for survivability. Yet more gear clutter
for me.
-------------------------------------------------------------------

Whether Kara was cleared or not, Gruul's Lair was on schedule
for Friday. This would test where we were and what we needed to
work on.

The instance is dead simple. One patroller - instantly somebody
dies; these guys hit like trucks. Two guards. Then already we
are at High King Maulgar. The fight is explained, and roles are
assigned.

I have my hands full spamming big heals on the MT. A mage
&quot;tanks&quot; Krosh, stealing his spell shield. A warlock takes
Olm, enslaving his pet and tanking him with it. Blindeye is the
first burn-down target, then Kiggler, then Krosh and Olm
together, then Maulgar.

We spend three hours wrestling with the ogre before calling it
a night. Our best performance gets the first two targets down.
Complete wipes are rare with the exit at our back, but most of
our resets are forced when the mage taking Krosh goes down.
We will need to try all of our mages in the role, and stock up
on cloth stamina gear to make healing them easier. His Greater
Fireballs ignore resistance gear; you have to Dampen Magic and
shield the mage. Often a fireball gets off before the spell
shield is up. Likewise with Olm, he often Deathcoils before
summoning the felhunter.

We now know where we stand: we can farm Kara and heroics for
a while yet, but need to look for stamina gear, and work on our
reactions. No further attempts on schedule for two weeks at least,
but we will get back there eventually.

We can now farm most of Kara; last Tuesday both of our groups
took down Prince. I was only on for half the run in my group, but
Card got not one but two weapons - the Maiden hammer I wanted so
much, enchanted on the spot with +81 healing, and the Staff of
Infinite Mysteries from Curator, which our mages had and the raid
leaders did not want to d/e. I rather wish I had been on Dorandy
for that fight - she would have really used it. But Dorandy was
used in the Wizard of Oz fight, and they practically forced me
to take the Ruby Slippers. Now if only I could get the Wicked
Witch's Hat...

(At this rate, I will have everything Kara has to offer in about
three weeks. Really, some of the other people in the guild need
to win stuff; they will make us stronger for Gruul.)

